'''Sir Francis "Frank" Joseph Edmund Beaurepaire''' (13 May 1891 &ndash; 29 May 1956) was an [[Australia]]n distance [[freestyle swimming|freestyle]] swimmer from the 1900s to the 1920s, who won three silver and three bronze medals, from the [[1908 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]] to the [[1924 Summer Olympics]] in [[Paris]], setting 15 world records.

He was also a decorated politician and businessman, serving for ten years in the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] and as [[Lord Mayor of Melbourne]] and building a multimillion-dollar tyre business empire, [[Beaurepaires and Olympic Tyres]].

==Early life==
Beaurepaire was born to Francis Edmund de Beaurepaire, a cable tram conductor, and Mary Edith Inman. Growing up in [[Melbourne]], Beaurepaire was educated at [[Albert Park, Victoria|Albert Park]] State School and [[Wesley College (Victoria)|Wesley College]].<ref name="ADB">{{Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Poynter|first=J.R.|id=A070234b|title=Beaurepaire, Frank|accessdate=1 November 2010}}</ref>

He had his first swimming lesson at the age of four, when his father dropped him into the sea water baths at [[South Melbourne, Victoria|South Melbourne]] with a rope tied around his waist. He often practised in the sea, close to where effluent was ejected into [[Port Phillip Bay]]. Later, when he had earned more money, he paid tuppence (2d. = two pence) to enter the now demolished Stubbs' South Melbourne Baths to train.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

His career was nearly ended when he was hospitalized for 12 months with [[rheumatic fever]]. However, encouraged by his schoolteacher and South Melbourne barber Tommy Horlock, who later became his coach, Beaurepaire fought off the ailment and resumed training with the [[Albert Park, Victoria|Albert Park]] State School Swimming Club.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

==Swimming career==
{{unreferenced section|date=March 2016}}
In 1906, a few months before his 15th birthday, Beaurepaire won the {{convert|220|yd|abbr=on}} and {{convert|440|yd|abbr=on}} freestyle at the Victorian championships. In 1908, he captured the {{convert|440|yd|abbr=on}}, 880&nbsp;yd and mile freestyle events at the Australian Championships to claim a spot in the [[1908 Summer Olympics]] team. On arrival in [[London]] with Horlock, he found that no arrangements had been made to pick them up, so they were forced to live with 16 pounds between them for a month, before officials became aware of their plight.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

Beaurepaire trained in London for three months before the Games. Unable to afford admission to [[swimming pool]]s, He was forced to train at [[Highgate Ponds]], at temperatures of 10&nbsp;°C. After a {{convert|15|mi|km|sing=on}} event in the [[River Thames]] prior to the Olympics he was numbed by the cold to such an extent that he collapsed and needed to be pulled from the water to avoid drowning. Later he won the {{convert|880|yd|abbr=on}} British Championship at [[Bradford]], defeating [[Henry Taylor (swimmer)|Henry Taylor]] of [[Lancashire]], and then proceeded to win the {{convert|220|yd|abbr=on}} event at [[Nottingham]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

Arriving at the Olympics, the competitors were confronted with a pool dug into the [[Athletics (track and field)|athletics]] track, with no filtration or chlorination, effectively being a muddy pond. Beaurepaire had caught [[influenza]] and finished in second and third in the 400&nbsp;m and 1500&nbsp;m freestyle respectively, both events being won by Taylor. He was eliminated in the heats of the 100&nbsp;m freestyle. He also finished fourth in the 4 × 200 m freestyle relay. After the Olympics, Beaurepaire again raced Taylor over {{convert|500|yd|abbr=on}} and one mile (1.6&nbsp;km) in Britain, winning the latter, in which some 20,000 spectators attended.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

Returning to Australia, he broke the {{convert|300|yd|abbr=on}} world record at the [[Melbourne City Baths]]. He reappeared prominently in 1910 when he won more than a dozen state and national titles, breaking the world {{convert|220|yd|abbr=on}} freestyle record in the process. His tour of the [[United Kingdom]] and continental [[Europe]] later that year resulted in world records in the 200&nbsp;m, 300&nbsp;m, {{convert|300|yd|abbr=on}}, 400&nbsp;m, 500&nbsp;m and {{convert|1000|yd|abbr=on}}, three of which were achieved in one race. He later swept all of the British championships from {{convert|100|yd|abbr=on}} up to one mile (1.6&nbsp;km). He competed in 41 first-class and championship races in four months, winning all of them.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

In 1911, after his long return by sea to Australia, he suffered his first defeat in three years and was forced to abandon the {{convert|440|yd|abbr=on}} freestyle event at the Australian Championships mid-race. Due to exhaustion, he took a break from competitive swimming to become a swimming instructor, earning 3 pounds 10 shillings (₤3/10/-) a week with the Victorian Department of Education as a physical education instructor.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

He was barred from Olympic competition by the [[International Swimming Federation]], which ruled him to be a professional, although he was not earning money for swimming. This ruled him out of the [[1912 Summer Olympics]] in [[Stockholm]], where the Australian 4&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;200&nbsp;m freestyle relay team won gold. The decision to bar him was reversed in 1914.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

He joined the [[Australian Defence Force]] as an infantryman, but was invalided and joined the [[YMCA]] services, and served in [[Egypt]], [[England]] and [[France]] before being hospitalized in 1917 with trench fever and gassing, and being returned to Australia.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

In February 1920, he won the Victorian championships, and soon after broke the 1000&nbsp;m world record and qualified for the [[1920 Summer Olympics]] in [[Antwerp]]. With swimming held in a near-freezing open-water canal, Beaurepaire abandoned the 400&nbsp;m freestyle mid-race due to illness, but managed to claim a bronze in the 1500&nbsp;m freestyle. He combined with [[William Herald]], [[Ivan Stedman]] and [[Harry Hay (swimmer)|Henry Hay]] to claim the silver medal in the 4&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;200&nbsp;m freestyle relay, some 21&nbsp;s behind the American squad.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

His sister [[Lily Beaurepaire|Lily]] also competed as part of the swimming and diving team, becoming the first brother-sister combination to represent [[Australia at the Summer Olympics]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

Back in Australia and later in [[Hawaii]] that year, he broke the {{convert|1000|yd|abbr=on}} and one mile (1.6&nbsp;km) records, and twice broke the 1000&nbsp;m and 1500&nbsp;m records. He was named as the captain of the swimming team for the [[1924 Summer Olympics]] in [[Paris]]. He was eliminated in the heats of the 400&nbsp;m freestyle, but at the age of 34 he claimed bronze in the 1500&nbsp;m freestyle, behind fellow Australian [[Boy Charlton]] and [[Sweden]]'s [[Arne Borg]]. He won a silver medal in the 4&nbsp;&times;&nbsp;200&nbsp;m freestyle relay alongside Charlton, [[Ernest Henry (swimmer)|Ernest Henry]] and [[Moss Christie]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

His last competitive appearance was his victory at [[Kew, Victoria]] in the State Championships in March 1928, which he won at 37 years of age. In all he set 15 world records over a span of 13 years, winning 79 Victorian titles, 11 British titles and a record 34 Australian titles. It was not until 2000 that [[Susie O'Neill]] broke his Australian record.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

==[[Beaurepaires]]==
{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}
In 1922, he was awarded the [[Royal Humane Society]] Gold Medal and 550 pounds, a significant sum in that era, after assisting another lifesaver, [[Jack Chalmers]]<ref>http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/chalmers-john-jack-12303</ref> in rescuing a shark attack victim at [[Coogee, New South Wales]], a suburb of [[Sydney]]. He used this to start [[Beaurepaires]], a tyres, wheels, batteries business, which had assets worth more than 8 million pounds at his death. The business now has over 230 stores in Australia. He attended the [[1932 Summer Olympics]] as a swimming official and judge.

==Local, state and federal politics==
{{unreferenced section|date=March 2016}}
From 1940-42, Beaurepaire was the [[Lord Mayor of Melbourne]]. He was knighted in the King's Birthday Honours of 1942.<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1083700&search_type=simple&showInd=true Profile], itsanhonour.gov.au; accessed 21 March 2016.</ref>

He was elected to the [[Victorian Legislative Council]] in 1942, serving until 1952. He was an unsuccessful candidate for [[Senate (Australia)|Senate]] for the [[United Australia Party]] in the [[Australian federal election, 1943|1943 federal election]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

In 1948 he was part of a delegation that went to [[London]] to lobby at the [[1948 Summer Olympics]] for Melbourne to host the [[1956 Summer Olympics]]. In 1949 Melbourne won the hosting rights and Beaurepaire was again re-elected as Lord Mayor. He hoped that he could preside over the Games. However, he died of a heart attack in the barber's chair at the [[Hotel Windsor (Melbourne)|Hotel Windsor]], just seven months before the Games. His son, [[Ian Francis Beaurepaire]], was also a Lord Mayor of Melbourne.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}

